<i>- Salmon, Queens.
- Schubert, Death and the Maiden.</i>

244
00:19:39,539 --> 00:19:41,541
<i>Is correct. That's
the sound of the gong.</i>

245
00:19:41,625 --> 00:19:44,919
<i>The winners of this year's grand
final are Queens' College, Cambridge.</i>

246
00:19:56,723 --> 00:20:00,143
Obviously, I take no pleasure
in showing that to you.

247
00:20:01,228 --> 00:20:03,730
But, as someone once
wrote, "To err is human."

248
00:20:03,813 --> 00:20:04,814
Anyone?

249
00:20:04,940 --> 00:20:07,025
<i>Alexander Pope's Essay On Man?</i>

250
00:20:07,150 --> 00:20:09,527
And, you know, I really
feel that with dedication

251
00:20:09,611 --> 00:20:12,614
and good old-fashioned teamwork,
that this could be our year.

252
00:20:12,739 --> 00:20:16,743
Which is why we're all assembled here
today. The Fantastic Four, if you will.

253
00:20:16,910 --> 00:20:20,038
Each with his or her own special powers.

254
00:20:20,121 --> 00:20:21,914
Colin, history, politics.

255
00:20:22,040 --> 00:20:24,042
Lucy, science, medicine.

256
00:20:24,125 --> 00:20:26,335
Alice, art and literature.

257
00:20:27,420 --> 00:20:31,048
And myself as a sort of
floating Renaissance man.

258
00:20:31,633 --> 00:20:34,010
Brian! Coaster, please.

259
00:20:36,346 --> 00:20:38,931
Now, the qualifying heats
are in two weeks' time.

260
00:20:39,015 --> 00:20:40,016
It's untelevised, of course,

261
00:20:40,141 --> 00:20:44,728
but we'll still need to be in good form
if we're to show them what we can do.

262
00:20:44,813 --> 00:20:46,022
- Brian.
- Shall I come along to that?

263
00:20:46,147 --> 00:20:48,023
- That won't be necessary.
- He is first reserve.

264
00:20:48,149 --> 00:20:51,026
- And I'd be more than happy.
- Team members only, Brian.

265
00:20:52,028 --> 00:20:53,821
I'm sure we can manage without you.

266
00:20:56,241 --> 00:20:57,617
I'm so sorry.

267
00:20:57,742 --> 00:20:59,618
Now, quantum mechanics, anyone?

268
00:21:01,329 --> 00:21:05,624
<i>Dear Spencer, just a quick note to
let you know how things are going here.</i>

269
00:21:05,750 --> 00:21:09,545
<i>My housemates are really interesting.</i>

270
00:21:09,629 --> 00:21:11,714
<i>It's great to meet people
from different backgrounds,</i>

271
00:21:11,840 --> 00:21:13,925
<i>and we are all having
a really good laugh.</i>

272
00:21:17,637 --> 00:21:19,221
I'm so sorry.

273
00:21:19,347 --> 00:21:22,016
<i>I've also become increasingly
politically active,</i>

274
00:21:22,142 --> 00:21:25,937
<i>and have so far protested against
apartheid, nuclear weapons, nuclear power,</i>

275
00:21:26,021 --> 00:21:29,149
<i>gay bashing and sexual
exploitation of women.</i>

276
00:21:29,316 --> 00:21:33,236
...rather than mere objects for
the sexual entertainment of men.

277
00:21:33,820 --> 00:21:36,447
<i>Did you know that,
under the bastard Tories,</i>

278
00:21:36,531 --> 00:21:41,035
<i>seven percent of the country
currently own 84% of the wealth?</i>

279
00:21:41,828 --> 00:21:44,247
<i>It's the same old story.
The rich get richer,</i>

280
00:21:44,331 --> 00:21:46,750
<i>and the most vulnerable
in our country suffer.</i>

281
00:21:47,626 --> 00:21:50,211
<i>Anyway, how are you?
How's the job hunt going?</i>

282
00:21:50,337 --> 00:21:53,715
<i>Got anything more permanent,
or are you still signing on?</i>

283
00:21:53,840 --> 00:21:57,218
<i>I know there's not much out there at
the moment, thanks to bloody Thatcher.</i>

284
00:21:57,219 --> 00:21:59,429
<i>But I'm sure something
will come up soon.</i>

285
00:21:59,513 --> 00:22:01,723
Hey! Piss off out of here.

286
00:22:01,848 --> 00:22:03,724
<i>Must sign off now,
as I've got a lecture.</i>

287
00:22:03,850 --> 00:22:06,018
<i>I'm currently wrestling
with the Romantic poets.</i>

288
00:22:06,144 --> 00:22:09,313
<i>Not literally, of course, as they
have been dead for some time now.</i>

289
00:22:10,816 --> 00:22:14,820
What do the so-called Romantic
Poets mean by the term "Romance"?

290
00:22:15,028 --> 00:22:16,946
It's certainly not hearts and flowers,

291
00:22:17,030 --> 00:22:19,824
though an appreciation of extreme beauty

292
00:22:20,033 --> 00:22:21,617
was a vital source of inspiration.

293
00:22:22,911 --> 00:22:28,124
But the notion of the Romantic poets
as swooning lovelorn fops is a fallacy.

294
00:22:28,834 --> 00:22:33,046
Byron, Wordsworth, Shelley in
particular, were all passionately...

295
00:22:33,046 --> 00:22:34,338
Come on!

296
00:22:36,842 --> 00:22:39,427
- Shouldn't you be at the qualifiers?
- That's the thing.

297
00:22:39,511 --> 00:22:41,221
Colin's been knocked over by a bus.

298
00:22:41,346 --> 00:22:43,723
He's okay, but it means
you're on the team.

299
00:22:43,849 --> 00:22:45,016
Yes!

300
00:22:47,144 --> 00:22:49,020
So glad that he's okay.

301
00:22:51,148 --> 00:22:54,317
Fifty questions, 30 minutes.
Conferring is allowed.

302
00:22:55,527 --> 00:22:59,822
And to make the grade, we need
a score of 70 percent or higher.

303
00:23:00,323 --> 00:23:03,909
Excuse me, but we're trying to do a
quiz here and it's against the clock.

304
00:23:04,035 --> 00:23:06,037
It's got to be done sometime.

305
00:23:06,037 --> 00:23:09,415
<i>This man has been sent from the
offices of University Challenge!</i>

306
00:23:15,839 --> 00:23:18,424
So, if we're ready.

307
00:23:19,843 --> 00:23:22,512
Sergeant Troy, Fanny Robin
and Bathsheba Everdene

308
00:23:22,637 --> 00:23:24,847
all appear in which
novel by Thomas Hardy?

309
00:23:24,931 --> 00:23:26,432
<i>- Return Of The Native.
- Return Of The Native.</i>

310
00:23:26,516 --> 00:23:28,643
<i>Actually I think it might be
Far From The Madding Crowd.</i>

311
00:23:28,643 --> 00:23:31,228
<i>- Oh, of course it is. Go with Brian.
- Far From The Madding Crowd.</i>

312
00:23:31,313 --> 00:23:32,314
Correct!

313
00:23:32,439 --> 00:23:36,025
Passer Domesticus is the scientific
name for which commonly known bird?

314
00:23:36,026 --> 00:23:37,736
- The common house sparrow.
- Correct.

315
00:23:37,819 --> 00:23:39,445
- Inflammation of the pancreas.
- Correct.

316
00:23:39,446 --> 00:23:41,322
- The Sistine Chapel.
- Is the correct answer.

317
00:23:41,448 --> 00:23:42,532
- The rings of Saturn.
- Correct.

318
00:23:42,616 --> 00:23:43,950
- The 38th parallel.
- Correct.

319
00:23:44,034 --> 00:23:45,827
- They carry their young in pouches.
- Correct.

320
00:23:45,911 --> 00:23:47,037
"My love is like a red, red rose."

321
00:23:47,120 --> 00:23:48,246
1664!

322
00:23:48,330 --> 00:23:50,123
- Prime numbers. Diaghilev. The spleen.
- Correct.

323
00:23:50,248 --> 00:23:52,416
The Berlin Airlift. Trick question.

324
00:23:52,542 --> 00:23:54,835
Gamma rays. Longshore
drift. The Venus de Milo.

325
00:23:54,836 --> 00:23:55,920
Correct.

326
00:23:56,046 --> 00:23:58,048
And your final question.

327
00:23:58,131 --> 00:24:00,925
Which decade saw the invention
of the replaceable razor,

328
00:24:01,051 --> 00:24:03,136
the formation of the Ford Motor Company,

329
00:24:03,220 --> 00:24:04,930
and the death of Oscar Wilde?

330
00:24:05,013 --> 00:24:06,222
- The 1890s.
- 1900s

331
00:24:06,223 --> 00:24:09,017
- 1890s.
- I'm pretty sure it's the 1900s.

332
00:24:10,227 --> 00:24:12,145
I am going to have to hurry you.

333
00:24:12,229 --> 00:24:13,730
Lucy, what do you think?

334
00:24:14,523 --> 00:24:16,650
Actually, I think Brian's right.

335
00:24:20,028 --> 00:24:22,613
Is the answer the 1900s?

336
00:24:23,031 --> 00:24:24,032
Correct.

337
00:24:26,743 --> 00:24:29,537
Right. Well, then.
Congratulations, team.

338
00:24:29,830 --> 00:24:33,250
Brian, glad to have you on board.

339
00:24:36,128 --> 00:24:38,130
- You were great.
- Thanks.

340
00:24:38,213 --> 00:24:39,547
Bye.

341
00:24:39,631 --> 00:24:41,549
Brian.

342
00:24:43,051 --> 00:24:45,011
I've never seen anything like it.

343
00:24:46,513 --> 00:24:48,723
You're a general knowledge God.

344
00:24:49,141 --> 00:24:51,518
<i>So what made you wanna
take the Challenge anyway?</i>

345
00:24:51,643 --> 00:24:53,019
<i>The Challenge!</i>

346
00:24:53,145 --> 00:24:57,023
Well, I want to be an actress,
or a TV presenter, or something.

347
00:24:57,232 --> 00:24:59,817
- It's all experience, isn't it?
- Yeah.

348
00:25:00,110 --> 00:25:02,737
How about you? How come
you know all that stuff?

349
00:25:02,821 --> 00:25:04,030
Misspent youth?

350
00:25:04,615 --> 00:25:08,910
And I suppose I've always just
liked that feeling of knowing things.

351
00:25:09,036 --> 00:25:10,746
For some reason it all
goes in and stays there.

352
00:25:10,829 --> 00:25:12,914
And it's just useless knowledge.

353
00:25:13,040 --> 00:25:15,625
You think there's such a
thing as useless knowledge?

354
00:25:15,751 --> 00:25:18,920
Well, sometimes. I wish I
hadn't learned to crochet.

355
00:25:19,046 --> 00:25:21,631
You are joking, aren't you?

356
00:25:23,634 --> 00:25:25,135
Oi, watch it.

357
00:25:27,346 --> 00:25:28,638
Hey!

358
00:25:29,514 --> 00:25:32,517
Better not. There might
be dog poo in there.

359
00:25:33,644 --> 00:25:35,145
Right.

360
00:25:35,228 --> 00:25:37,647
Oh, God, I just
remembered! Mask workshop.

361
00:25:37,731 --> 00:25:40,817
I've gotta run. See you
at the next rehearsal.

362
00:25:42,736 --> 00:25:45,447
Alice, what are you doing on Friday?

363
00:25:47,032 --> 00:25:48,450
It's just, it's my birthday.

364
00:25:48,450 --> 00:25:50,410
You're having a party.
Well, of course I'll come.

365
00:25:50,535 --> 00:25:54,121
Not a party, exactly. I was,
I was thinking more dinner.

366
00:25:55,040 --> 00:25:56,541
Or something...

367
00:25:57,542 --> 00:25:59,710
Just me and you?

368
00:26:00,629 --> 00:26:01,921
Mmm-hmm.

369
00:26:04,216 --> 00:26:06,134
Brian, I'd love to.

370
00:26:06,843 --> 00:26:08,219
Is the correct answer.

371
00:26:11,139 --> 00:26:13,349
Okay. Friday.

372
00:26:52,723 --> 00:26:54,349
Something wrong?

373
00:26:54,433 --> 00:26:58,311
No. No, I just think you could've
put in a bit more effort, that's all.

374
00:27:01,648 --> 00:27:03,524
So, where are you taking me?

375
00:27:13,744 --> 00:27:16,037
It's a good job I reserved a table.

376
00:27:16,038 --> 00:27:18,040
- This is great.
- Are you sure?

377
00:27:18,123 --> 00:27:20,917
It looked posher from outside,
with all the candles and everything.

378
00:27:21,043 --> 00:27:24,212
But I love pizza. And
they do one with chips on.

379
00:27:25,714 --> 00:27:27,340
"King Edward."

380
00:27:29,927 --> 00:27:34,222
Hello. Hi. Excuse me.

381
00:27:39,144 --> 00:27:42,522
The Lambrusco Bianco,

382
00:27:43,816 --> 00:27:45,442
could you tell me what year it is?

383
00:27:45,442 --> 00:27:46,651
1985.

384
00:27:48,237 --> 00:27:52,324
No, I know. I know what year it
is. I meant what year is the wine?

385
00:27:52,449 --> 00:27:53,533
1985.

386
00:27:54,827 --> 00:27:56,119
Very well.

387
00:27:56,829 --> 00:28:00,040
We'll have the white
Lambrusco Bianco '85, please.

388
00:28:04,837 --> 00:28:07,714
Look! Breadsticks. Hooray!

389
00:28:25,315 --> 00:28:28,609
You know, I think I'm going
to have these garlic mushrooms.

390
00:28:28,735 --> 00:28:31,446
Well, you won't be
snogging anyone tonight.

391
00:28:36,744 --> 00:28:39,413
So, have you had many boyfriends, or...

392
00:28:40,539 --> 00:28:43,124
- Where did that come from?
- I don't know. I'm just curious.

393
00:28:43,250 --> 00:28:45,835
What, you really want to know? Okay.

394
00:28:47,546 --> 00:28:50,340
When I was 15, there was Charlie,

395
00:28:50,424 --> 00:28:53,343
who was the lead singer in this band.

396
00:28:54,219 --> 00:28:56,429
He was incredibly handsome.

397
00:28:57,222 --> 00:28:58,348
Gorgeous.

398
00:28:58,432 --> 00:29:01,643
I left him for Rufus. We
then had a nine-month affair.

399
00:29:01,727 --> 00:29:03,645
I then went out with his best friend.

400
00:29:03,729 --> 00:29:06,815
And then I had a fling with a
lovely Italian guy called Alessandro.

401
00:29:07,816 --> 00:29:09,651
He was, like, skinny
because he was younger,

402
00:29:09,735 --> 00:29:11,820
but he had, like,
muscles and definition.

403
00:29:11,945 --> 00:29:16,032
Gregor was lovely, but
incredibly possessive.

404
00:29:17,034 --> 00:29:21,038
In the end we had to call the
police and I think he was deported.

405
00:29:22,039 --> 00:29:24,624
And I think that that's about it.

406
00:29:26,418 --> 00:29:30,839
Funny, isn't it, how many of them
end up being mad, or suicidal?

407
00:29:32,049 --> 00:29:33,842
- Or in prison.
- I know.

408
00:29:33,926 --> 00:29:37,429
Rufus, you know the performance
artist, the one who set fire to himself?

409
00:29:38,639 --> 00:29:41,350
He used to say I had the kiss of death.

410
00:29:42,935 --> 00:29:45,812
That's why I'm giving it all
up. Concentrate on my work.

411
00:29:46,814 --> 00:29:49,024
Get me to a nunnery.

412
00:29:49,650 --> 00:29:52,736
- Hamlet, Act 3, Scene 1.
- You never stop, do you?

413
00:29:53,237 --> 00:29:55,447
What do your parents do again?

414
00:29:57,032 --> 00:29:59,743
Mum works in a shoe shop and Dad's dead.

415
00:30:01,537 --> 00:30:04,915
It's all right. You don't need to get
all serious. It was a long time ago.

416
00:30:05,040 --> 00:30:06,541
What happened?

417
00:30:06,625 --> 00:30:09,044
Well, he was a salesman. Double glazing.

418
00:30:09,128 --> 00:30:13,048
You know, working on commission.
Long, long hours. He hated it.

419
00:30:13,841 --> 00:30:18,136
Anyway, it must've been eating away at him
because one day he just fell over, apparently.

420
00:30:18,637 --> 00:30:22,432
In this old couple's living room,
selling polyurethane windows.

421
00:30:22,850 --> 00:30:25,727
Forty-one years old. Let's, uh...

422
00:30:27,646 --> 00:30:30,148
Let's get another drink. Excuse me.

423
00:30:30,232 --> 00:30:33,443
- Do you think about him?
- Yeah, of course. Every day.

424
00:30:34,320 --> 00:30:38,449
But we never really got to know
one another. Not as adults, anyway.

425
00:30:39,450 --> 00:30:42,244
I really only remember sitting
in front of the telly with him.

426
00:30:42,328 --> 00:30:44,121
Quizzes. He loved quizzes.

427
00:30:44,246 --> 00:30:46,623
Nature programmes, anything educational.

428
00:30:46,749 --> 00:30:48,041
Knowledge.

429
00:30:48,125 --> 00:30:50,919
That was the key, he
said, to being happy.

430
00:30:51,337 --> 00:30:54,048
Not ending up doing some job you hate.

431
00:30:57,635 --> 00:30:58,844
Where's that waiter?

432
00:30:58,927 --> 00:31:01,638
- He'd have loved you.
- You think so?

433
00:31:02,431 --> 00:31:05,142
Of course. Don't you?

434
00:31:06,018 --> 00:31:07,519
Don't know.

435
00:31:08,646 --> 00:31:11,523
I think he might've thought I
was a bit weird, to be honest.

436
00:31:11,649 --> 00:31:14,318
- Oh, he'd have been very proud of you.
- Why?

437
00:31:15,027 --> 00:31:18,739
Going to university.
Star of the quiz team.

438
00:31:20,240 --> 00:31:25,245
- Doing all the things he never got to do.
- Yeah, maybe. Maybe.

439
00:31:26,830 --> 00:31:28,248
Anyway, Alice, excuse me,

440
00:31:28,332 --> 00:31:31,126
do you mind if I just
pop off to the loo?

441
00:31:33,837 --> 00:31:37,215
You are such a lovely man.

442
00:31:47,726 --> 00:31:49,644
I'm sorry about tonight.

443
00:31:50,437 --> 00:31:53,022
I don't usually cry until
much later in the evening.

444
00:31:53,023 --> 00:31:54,941
You mustn't apologise.

445
00:31:55,442 --> 00:31:58,319
It was very illuminating.

446
00:32:00,614 --> 00:32:02,616
Brian, what are you doing at Christmas?

447
00:32:02,741 --> 00:32:06,828
Just the usual. Watching telly
with Mum, eating cheap chocolate.

448
00:32:07,913 --> 00:32:09,748
That kind of thing, really. Why?

449
00:32:09,832 --> 00:32:12,417
Well, it's just that we've
got this cottage in Suffolk.

450
00:32:12,418 --> 00:32:15,129
And it's so dull when it's
just Michael and Rose and me.

451
00:32:15,212 --> 00:32:17,422
- Who are Michael and Rose?
- My parents.

452
00:32:18,215 --> 00:32:20,842
I thought, maybe you
could come and stay.

453
00:32:24,847 --> 00:32:29,017
- I can't really leave Mum.
- No, but after Christmas. For New Year.

454
00:32:29,018 --> 00:32:31,437
My parents keep themselves to
themselves most of the time,

455
00:32:31,520 --> 00:32:35,941
so it'd just be me and you,
walking, reading, hanging out.

456
00:32:36,025 --> 00:32:39,945
- But if the idea fills you with dread...
- Yes!

457
00:32:40,946 --> 00:32:45,450
No... Yes... That would be really good.

458
00:32:46,327 --> 00:32:47,828
It's decided, then.

459
00:32:49,538 --> 00:32:50,830
Thank you.

460
00:32:55,419 --> 00:32:56,545
Good night.

461
00:33:14,230 --> 00:33:16,732
So I take it it went okay then, Romeo?

462
00:33:17,650 --> 00:33:20,611
Well, you know, it went all right.

463
00:33:21,445 --> 00:33:23,530
So is love in the air?

464
00:33:23,614 --> 00:33:25,240
Not love.

465
00:33:26,534 --> 00:33:29,620
- Like.
- Like is in the air.

466
00:33:52,226 --> 00:33:54,228
Mum, I'm home.

467
00:33:56,313 --> 00:33:57,439
Mum?

468
00:34:10,619 --> 00:34:14,247
Brian! Get out! Get out now!

469
00:34:16,333 --> 00:34:21,421
<i>Our obligation to make our own
individual contributions, however small...</i>

470
00:34:29,013 --> 00:34:31,724
<i>His name's Des, a widower
from down the road.</i>

471
00:34:31,849 --> 00:34:33,642
<i>An ice cream man.</i>

472
00:34:34,018 --> 00:34:37,146
<i>You know when he's coming round
because you can hear the chimes.</i>

473
00:34:37,229 --> 00:34:40,440
<i>They've been keeping each
other company ever since I left.</i>

474
00:34:40,524 --> 00:34:42,442
<i>Twice a day, sometimes.</i>

475
00:34:42,818 --> 00:34:44,319
These are nice, Julie.

476
00:34:44,445 --> 00:34:47,030
Little sausages wrapped in bacon, Des.

477
00:34:48,324 --> 00:34:50,034
Eat your sprouts, you'll get rickets.

478
00:34:50,117 --> 00:34:53,328
Rickets is calcium deficiency,
Mum. You're thinking of scurvy.

479
00:34:53,412 --> 00:34:56,415
