- I'm sorry about...
- Look, Brian.

799
00:58:02,636 --> 00:58:04,638
I got drunk. I was having a nice time

800
00:58:04,721 --> 00:58:08,433
and I fancied a bit of
human, whatever, contact.

801
00:58:08,851 --> 00:58:14,022
And I made a mistake. Misread the signals.
Very embarrassing, but not a big deal.

802
00:58:14,148 --> 00:58:16,024
I'm sure I'll learn to love again.

803
00:58:25,242 --> 00:58:28,245
Have you got your fluffy mascot
packed ready for the big match?

804
00:58:28,328 --> 00:58:30,121
No, think it's all a bit
silly, that mascot stuff.

805
00:58:30,247 --> 00:58:32,832
Brian, you're such a maverick!

806
00:58:32,916 --> 00:58:34,250
So, are you gonna come
along and watch, then?

807
00:58:34,334 --> 00:58:36,544
What, see you in action?
You must be joking.

808
00:58:36,628 --> 00:58:38,421
I wish you would.
There's a free minibus.

809
00:58:38,547 --> 00:58:40,549
Yeah, what do you care anyway?

810
00:58:41,425 --> 00:58:43,927
Just like you to be there, that's all.

811
00:58:44,053 --> 00:58:47,639
Only don't say anything to my mate
Spencer. He'd only take a piss.

812
00:58:47,723 --> 00:58:49,015
Oh, my God, Patrick!

813
00:58:51,018 --> 00:58:55,147
Brian, I hope that's not an
alcoholic beverage in your hand there.

814
00:58:55,230 --> 00:58:57,315
- Big day tomorrow and all.
- Why's that, then?

815
00:58:57,441 --> 00:58:59,443
'Cause he's the team's
star player, aren't you?

816
00:58:59,443 --> 00:59:02,112
<i>- What team?
- This year's University Challenge team.</i>

817
00:59:04,239 --> 00:59:05,823
- You're joking?
- No.

818
00:59:05,824 --> 00:59:07,116
You?

819
00:59:07,242 --> 00:59:09,118
Me, Alice, Lucy and Patrick.

820
00:59:09,244 --> 00:59:11,037
- What, actually on telly?
- Yeah.

821
00:59:11,038 --> 00:59:14,833
- Bloody hell, Brian. You dark horse.
- Something funny?

822
00:59:14,917 --> 00:59:16,627
No, not at all, mate.

823
00:59:16,752 --> 00:59:19,045
Just always wondered what
kind of bizarre nerdy swot

824
00:59:19,046 --> 00:59:21,548
would wanna go on a programme like
that, turns out it's you, Brian.

825
00:59:21,632 --> 00:59:24,134
- I didn't want to tell you.
- So...

826
00:59:24,218 --> 00:59:26,929
Where are you studying, mate?

827
00:59:27,429 --> 00:59:30,348
Actually, Patrick, Spencer
is taking a year out.

828
00:59:30,432 --> 00:59:33,435
- No, I'm not. I'm unemployed.
- I see.

829
00:59:33,519 --> 00:59:36,438
- Social Security, then.
- That's right, yeah.

830
00:59:36,522 --> 00:59:39,149
Or he was, until those bastards
decided to prosecute him.

831
00:59:39,233 --> 00:59:42,444
- Are you being prosecuted, Spencer?
- Only for fiddling his dole.

832
00:59:42,528 --> 00:59:44,321
Do you think you'll go to prison?

833
00:59:44,446 --> 00:59:46,239
I'm sure if he didn't
do it, he'll be fine.

834
00:59:46,323 --> 00:59:49,951
But he did. He had to, didn't
you? Just to make a living wage.

835
00:59:50,035 --> 00:59:52,328
- So you did have a job? -
Bit of cash-in-hand, yeah.

836
00:59:52,413 --> 00:59:54,331
Well, then, I have to
say best of luck, mate.

837
00:59:54,415 --> 00:59:56,917
Well, hang on. Do you have any idea
how much the government pay a week?

838
00:59:57,042 --> 00:59:58,835
So, there's obviously
plenty of work out there.

839
00:59:58,919 --> 01:00:00,629
That's a little harsh,
Patrick, some people...

840
01:00:00,713 --> 01:00:03,424
- There's three million unemployed.
- Yes, but he isn't one of them, is he?

841
01:00:03,424 --> 01:00:04,550
If his job wasn't paying him enough,

842
01:00:04,633 --> 01:00:05,925
he should get on his bike
and find a better one.

843
01:00:06,051 --> 01:00:08,344
He certainly shouldn't steal
from law abiding citizens...

844
01:00:09,346 --> 01:00:11,639
Here's a question for
you, mate! What is my name?

845
01:00:11,724 --> 01:00:12,850
- What?
- Spencer put him down.

846
01:00:12,933 --> 01:00:14,643
You heard me, what is my name?

847
01:00:14,852 --> 01:00:16,812
- I'll have to hurry you.
- Spencer, I'm serious, put him down.

848
01:00:16,812 --> 01:00:18,438
- My name is?
- Patrick, say Spencer.

849
01:00:18,522 --> 01:00:20,232
- Spencer, Spencer.
- Correct.

850
01:00:20,316 --> 01:00:23,652
And if you got something to say to
me, you say it to my face! All right?

851
01:00:27,323 --> 01:00:28,532
Patrick.

852
01:00:29,450 --> 01:00:30,742
Spencer!

853
01:01:03,943 --> 01:01:05,653
The party's over.

854
01:01:10,741 --> 01:01:12,951
Your friend was looking for you.

855
01:01:14,119 --> 01:01:17,539
- Why do you think I'm sitting out here?
- Yeah.

856
01:01:18,040 --> 01:01:20,042
Quite a handful, isn't he?

857
01:01:24,546 --> 01:01:26,130
Is Alice all right?

858
01:01:30,928 --> 01:01:35,349
Brian, sometimes the people
you care about the most just

859
01:01:35,933 --> 01:01:37,935
basically they don't
give a toss about you.

860
01:01:38,018 --> 01:01:39,936
Look, you don't know that.

861
01:01:40,020 --> 01:01:41,730
Well, go on, then. Try. I dare you.

862
01:01:41,814 --> 01:01:44,024
Go and see her right now
and tell her how you feel

863
01:01:44,024 --> 01:01:46,818
and then maybe we can
all get some bloody peace.

864
01:02:19,018 --> 01:02:20,853
Come on, Alice, open up.

865
01:02:25,524 --> 01:02:27,817
Oh, my God, Brian. What's up?

866
01:02:28,819 --> 01:02:31,029
Could I come in, do you think?

867
01:02:31,030 --> 01:02:33,824
- I'll get some clothes on.
- All right.

868
01:02:41,540 --> 01:02:43,250
Okay, you can come in.

869
01:02:46,420 --> 01:02:49,047
All right, I'm sorry about tonight.

870
01:02:50,216 --> 01:02:52,218
I love Spencer, but he can
be such a wanker sometimes.

871
01:02:52,218 --> 01:02:54,053
Oh, no, don't worry about it.

872
01:02:54,553 --> 01:02:58,431
I know I probably shouldn't say this,
but it was actually quite exciting.

873
01:02:58,516 --> 01:03:00,726
Like Roman gladiators
or something and that...

874
01:03:03,354 --> 01:03:05,230
I've been dying to do that for so long.

875
01:03:07,233 --> 01:03:08,734
Oh, please don't.

876
01:03:08,818 --> 01:03:11,153
What? We did it before.

877
01:03:11,320 --> 01:03:14,031
We've got a big day tomorrow. Can
we just talk about this some other...

878
01:03:14,114 --> 01:03:16,032
I love you, Alice.

879
01:03:18,327 --> 01:03:19,745
At least, I think I do.

880
01:03:21,038 --> 01:03:23,623
I thought that we had
something. Didn't we, Alice?

881
01:03:23,749 --> 01:03:28,920
Some kind of chemistry, or
electricity, or whatever but...

882
01:03:32,424 --> 01:03:34,551
All right, mate?

883
01:03:39,515 --> 01:03:41,225
We were talking...

884
01:03:46,230 --> 01:03:48,148
Bri, Bri.

885
01:03:49,733 --> 01:03:53,027
Look, I know you might not believe this,
I was actually putting a good word for you.

886
01:03:53,154 --> 01:03:54,822
Spencer, mate, you were half-naked.

887
01:03:54,947 --> 01:03:57,616
We was only fooling around,
it's nothing serious.

888
01:03:59,952 --> 01:04:03,538
Look, Bri, if you've got something to
say, just say it 'cause this is stupid.

889
01:04:04,540 --> 01:04:07,042
You knew how I felt about her.

890
01:04:07,126 --> 01:04:10,712
You knew, Spence. I told you. And
you couldn't keep away, could you?

891
01:04:10,838 --> 01:04:13,048
- She started it.
- Well, that's all right then, isn't it?

892
01:04:13,132 --> 01:04:15,634
And what about the fight? Was
that somebody else's fault as well?

893
01:04:15,634 --> 01:04:17,552
What do you expect? He was
trying to make me look stupid.

894
01:04:17,636 --> 01:04:18,928
So you resorted to violence?

895
01:04:19,013 --> 01:04:20,723
No, I didn't resort to it.
Violence was my first choice.

896
01:04:20,848 --> 01:04:22,724
All right, that's cool.
That's very hard, mate.

897
01:04:22,850 --> 01:04:26,228
Well, I didn't exactly see you going
out of your way to help me, did I, Judas?

898
01:04:26,228 --> 01:04:28,813
- I was sticking up for you!
- Oh, that's what you were doing.

899
01:04:28,939 --> 01:04:30,649
You see, for a moment I
thought you were just flapping

900
01:04:30,733 --> 01:04:33,235
your social conscience around
in front of your girlfriend!

901
01:04:33,319 --> 01:04:35,738
You made me feel like a prick, Bri.

902
01:04:35,821 --> 01:04:38,448
- You are a prick.
- Don't push your luck, Jackson.

903
01:04:38,532 --> 01:04:41,243
What is it, Spencer, this
need to smash things up?

904
01:04:41,327 --> 01:04:43,454
You know, it's all very well
messing your own life up,

905
01:04:43,537 --> 01:04:45,539
but why do you have to do it with
people that care about themselves?

906
01:04:45,623 --> 01:04:47,750
People who're trying
to achieve something,

907
01:04:47,833 --> 01:04:50,627
- make something of their lives?
- What, like you, you mean?

908
01:04:51,629 --> 01:04:54,548
- You're just jealous of me.
- Jealous? What, of you?

909
01:04:55,049 --> 01:04:58,218
You think because you read a couple
books you're suddenly better than me?

910
01:04:58,344 --> 01:04:59,845
That's not what Alice seems to think.

911
01:05:07,520 --> 01:05:10,439
I want you gone, Spencer. I
want you on the first train.

912
01:05:10,439 --> 01:05:13,233
I don't care how much trouble
you're in. You've gotta go.

913
01:05:13,943 --> 01:05:17,237
Brian. Where are you going, Brian?

914
01:05:22,326 --> 01:05:23,827
I'm sorry.

915
01:05:26,747 --> 01:05:30,542
Wake up! We have to be in
Manchester in two hours.

916
01:05:30,835 --> 01:05:32,044
Brian!

917
01:05:35,715 --> 01:05:37,425
Two minutes, Brian.

918
01:05:41,929 --> 01:05:46,224
Patrick, if it's any consolation,
I'm sure they can cover that up

919
01:05:46,350 --> 01:05:48,518
- with make-up or...
- Just get in, will you?

920
01:05:51,522 --> 01:05:52,731
Hey, there.

921
01:05:55,943 --> 01:05:58,028
Here we are then, the Fantastic Four.

922
01:06:04,243 --> 01:06:07,329
The duodenum and ileum form
part of which bodily system?

923
01:06:07,413 --> 01:06:08,914
- The digestive system.
- Correct.

924
01:06:09,040 --> 01:06:12,126
<i>The Wild Duck and Rosmersholm
are by which Nordic playwright?</i>

925
01:06:12,251 --> 01:06:16,046
Patrick, can I just ask, do you think
by some kind of freakish coincidence,

926
01:06:16,047 --> 01:06:17,840
these questions are
going to be on the show?

927
01:06:17,923 --> 01:06:20,842
Because if they're not, it's a
bit of a waste of time, isn't it?

928
01:06:20,843 --> 01:06:24,513
It's a warm-up, Brian, for those of us
who aren't feeling too fresh this morning.

929
01:06:24,639 --> 01:06:27,433
What about Alice, then?
Late night was it, Alice?

930
01:06:27,516 --> 01:06:29,726
- Not here, Brian.
- Right, so,

931
01:06:29,852 --> 01:06:32,521
just the four of us today or
is someone hiding in the back?

932
01:06:32,647 --> 01:06:33,939
Later, okay?

933
01:06:34,023 --> 01:06:36,150
Will someone please tell
me what the hell's going on?

934
01:06:36,233 --> 01:06:38,235
I know. Let's listen to some music.

935
01:06:56,921 --> 01:06:59,214
Finally. I'll let them know you're here.

936
01:07:00,341 --> 01:07:01,717
Brian, where are you going?

937
01:07:01,842 --> 01:07:03,844
Just give me five minutes. All right?

938
01:07:03,844 --> 01:07:05,846
- We're already late because of you.
- Leave him, Patrick.

939
01:07:05,930 --> 01:07:08,223
All right. But five minutes only.

940
01:07:10,017 --> 01:07:11,435
Mum, it's not for hours yet.

941
01:07:11,519 --> 01:07:14,647
I know. We set off at dawn. We
thought we'd make a day of it.

942
01:07:14,730 --> 01:07:16,148
I brought Des along.
You don't mind, do you?

943
01:07:16,232 --> 01:07:17,650
No. No, that's fine.

944
01:07:18,234 --> 01:07:21,028
- What do you think, Bri?
- I've got to go.

945
01:07:22,530 --> 01:07:24,240
Brian, is something wrong?

946
01:07:24,240 --> 01:07:26,242
What could possibly be wrong, Mum?

947
01:07:26,325 --> 01:07:28,243
Is it Des, Brian?

948
01:07:28,327 --> 01:07:31,621
Brian? Get back here
this minute, young man!

949
01:07:37,628 --> 01:07:40,047
Brian, I wish your Dad
was here today, too.

950
01:07:40,131 --> 01:07:41,841
But that's not going to happen, is it?

951
01:07:42,717 --> 01:07:45,344
I'm sorry you don't like Des, but I do.

952
01:07:45,428 --> 01:07:48,139
And he likes me. And he makes me laugh.

